  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_1160",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Characterizing Deterministic-Prover Zero Knowledge",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Nir Bitansky",
        "email": "nirbitan@tau",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Arka Rai Choudhuri",
        "email": "ilachoud@cs",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Randomness  is  typically  thought  to  be  essential  for  zero  knowledge  protocols.  Following  this  intuition,  Goldreich   and  Oren (Journal  of  Cryptology 94)  proved  that  auxiliary-input  zero  knowledge  cannot  be  achieved  with  a  deterministic  prover.  On  the  other  hand,  positive  results  are  only  known  in  the  honest-verifier  setting,  or  when  the  prover  is  given  at  least  a  restricted  source  of  entropy.\n\nWe  prove  that  removing (or  just  bounding)  the  verifier's  auxiliary  input,  deterministic-prover  zero  knowledge  becomes  feasible:\n\n-  Assuming  non-interactive  witness-indistinguishable  proofs   and  subexponential  indistinguishability  obfuscation   and  one-way  functions,  we  construct  deterministic-prover  zero-knowledge  arguments  for $\\mathsf{NP}\\cap  \\mathsf{coNP}$  against  verifiers  with  bounded  non-uniform  auxiliary  input.\n\n-  Assuming  also  keyless  hash  functions  that  are  collision-resistant  against  bounded-auxiliary-input  quasipolynomial-time  attackers,  we  construct  similar  arguments  for  all  of $\\mathsf{NP}$.\n\nTogether  with  the  result  of  Goldreich   and  Oren,  this  characterizes  when  deterministic-prover  zero  knowledge  is  feasible.  We  also  demonstrate  the  necessity  of  strong  assumptions,  by  showing  that  deterministic  prover  zero  knowledge  arguments  for  a  given  language  imply  witness  encryption  for  that  language.  We  further  prove  that  such  arguments  can  always  be  collapsed  to  two  messages   and  be  made  laconic.  These  implications  rely  on  a  more  general  connection  with  the  notion  of  predictable  arguments  by  Faonio,  Nielsen,   and  Venturi (PKC 17).",
    "keywords": [
      "zero knowledge"
    ],
    "category": "Foundations",
    "publication_info": "Published by the IACR in TCC 2020",
    "last_updated": "2020-09-25",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
